Yes, and that's exactly the right behavior. Here's what Agno does in `_set_memory_manager`:

```python
if team.memory_manager is None:
    team.memory_manager = MemoryManager(model=team.model, db=team.db)  # default
else:
    # OURS — just fills in model/db if we didn't set them
    if team.memory_manager.model is None:
        team.memory_manager.model = team.model
    if team.memory_manager.db is None:
        team.memory_manager.db = team.db
```

So: **yes, our custom `MemoryManager` fully replaces the default one.** Agno only builds the default when `team.memory_manager is None`. Since we pass ours at construction, it goes into the `else` branch — which just fills in `model` (from `team.model`) and `db` (from `team.db`) if we didn't supply them explicitly. We passed `db` so Agno leaves it alone; it only fills in `model` since we didn't set one.

The result is our `MemoryManager` is the one that runs — with our `memory_capture_instructions` — and the default is never created. Nothing is merged or stacked.

